---
import Pipeline from "../components/Pipeline.astro";
import Stage from "../components/Stage.astro";
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
---

<Base
  title="chainscope · the supply chain, in six surfaces"
  description="A visual, scrollable explainer for software supply chain security. Six attack surfaces, six real incidents, the defense that would have stopped each."
>
  <article class="article">
    <p class="kicker">A field notebook for software supply chain security</p>

    <h1 class="title">
      Six places where someone else's code becomes yours.
    </h1>

    <p class="lede">
      The binary running on your laptop, your phone, your production cluster
      passed through several hands before it reached you. Most readers can name
      one or two of those hands. There are six. An attacker who owns any of them
      owns the artifact, and you cannot tell the difference by looking.
    </p>

    <p class="lede">
      This page is a tour of those six surfaces. For each, a recent attack that
      hit it. For each, the defense that would have caught the attack early.
      Names, hashes, commit IDs, links to the actual transparency log entries
      where they exist. Read in order, the second time across you will see the
      whole chain at once.
    </p>

    <Pipeline />

    <Stage
      id="source"
      num="01"
      title="Source"
      question="Who is allowed to change the code, and how do you know they meant to?"
    >
      <p class="lead">
        On a quiet evening in early 2023, the maintainer of a small compression
        library called <code>xz-utils</code> received a polite email. A new
        contributor, "Jia Tan," wanted to help. The maintainer was burned out.
        Patches kept coming, and they were good. Eighteen months later, Jia Tan
        had commit access. Six months after that, almost every Linux server on
        Earth shipped a backdoor in <code>sshd</code>.
      </p>

      <div class="incident">
        <span class="incident-tag">Anchor &middot; xz-utils &middot; 2024-03-29</span>
        <p class="incident-headline">
          CVE-2024-3094: a multi-year social engineering operation almost
          shipped a remote SSH backdoor to every major Linux distribution.
        </p>
        <p>
          The malicious code did not live in the Git repository. It was in the
          release tarball, hidden inside test fixtures and stitched together by
          obfuscated <code>configure</code> macros at build time. Anyone reading
          the source on GitHub saw nothing. Anyone running <code>./configure
          &amp;&amp; make</code> from the released tarball got a backdoor.
        </p>
        <p class="incident-meta">
          <a
            href="https://www.openwall.com/lists/oss-security/2024/03/29/4"
            >Andres Freund's original disclosure</a
          >
          &middot;
          <a href="https://research.swtch.com/xz-script">Russ Cox's reconstruction</a>
        </p>
      </div>

      <p>
        The first surface is the source itself. Two questions sit underneath it.
        Who can write to the repository, and once they have written, can a
        reader prove that what they wrote is what reached the build server?
      </p>

      <ul class="defenses">
        <li>
          <span class="defense-name">commit signing</span>
          <span class="defense-desc">
            Sigstore <code>gitsign</code> or GPG signatures bind a commit to a
            real identity. A reviewer can ask: "is this commit from the person
            whose laptop I trust?" Without it, an attacker who steals an SSH
            key can author commits as anyone.
          </span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="defense-name">branch protection</span>
          <span class="defense-desc">
            Required reviews, signed-commit enforcement, and protected tags
            prevent a single compromised maintainer from pushing straight to
            <code>main</code> or rewriting a release tag after the fact.
          </span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="defense-name">tarball reproducibility</span>
          <span class="defense-desc">
            If the released tarball is byte-identical to <code>git
            archive</code> on the tagged commit, there is nowhere for a
            tarball-only payload to hide. xz worked precisely because the
            tarball and the repository disagreed.
          </span>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </Stage>

    <Stage
      id="deps"
      num="02"
      title="Dependencies"
      question="Your code is mostly other people's code. Whose, exactly?"
    >
      <p class="lead">
        On 14 September 2025, a worm started spreading across the npm registry.
        It did not need a zero-day. It needed one developer to publish from a
        machine that had been phished. The worm read that developer's npm
        token, listed every package they could publish to, injected itself into
        each, and pushed new versions. Within a day, hundreds of packages were
        compromised; within weeks, tens of thousands of repositories carried
        traces.
      </p>

      <div class="incident">
        <span class="incident-tag">Anchor &middot; Shai-Hulud worm &middot; 2025-09 / 2025-11</span>
        <p class="incident-headline">
          The first self-replicating worm in a public package registry. Each
          infected developer becomes a launcher for the next wave.
        </p>
        <p>
          The payload also reached for GitHub Actions: stolen tokens were used
          to register self-hosted runners, exfiltrate the secret store via
          <code>toJSON(secrets)</code>, and plant backdoored workflows.
          Shai-Hulud 2.0 in November was wider, with over 25,000 malicious
          repositories created by automation alone.
        </p>
        <p class="incident-meta">
          <a
            href="https://unit42.paloaltonetworks.com/npm-supply-chain-attack/"
            >Unit 42 writeup</a
          >
          &middot;
          <a
            href="https://www.cisa.gov/news-events/alerts/2025/09/23/widespread-supply-chain-compromise-impacting-npm-ecosystem"
            >CISA alert</a
          >
        </p>
      </div>

      <p>
        Most projects have more lines of dependency code than first-party code.
        Each one is a hand that has touched the artifact.
      </p>

      <ul class="defenses">
        <li>
          <span class="defense-name">SBOM</span>
          <span class="defense-desc">
            A Software Bill of Materials lists every dependency, version, and
            hash. When a CVE breaks tomorrow, the question "are we exposed?"
            becomes a grep instead of an audit.
          </span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="defense-name">version pinning</span>
          <span class="defense-desc">
            Lockfiles and hash-pinned dependencies make "an attacker pushed a
            new version" not the same as "your build pulled it." Floating
            ranges (<code>^1.2</code>, <code>~3.4</code>) let worms walk in.
          </span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="defense-name">scorecards</span>
          <span class="defense-desc">
            OpenSSF Scorecard automates the question "does this package look
            like it is maintained by humans who care?" It checks 2FA, signed
            releases, recent activity, and branch protection on the upstream.
          </span>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </Stage>

    <Stage
      id="build"
      num="03"
      title="Build"
      question="The artifact is not the source. Who turned one into the other?"
    >
      <p class="lead">
        On 14 March 2025, every version tag of a popular GitHub Action called
        <code>tj-actions/changed-files</code> was rewritten to point at a
        single malicious commit. Pipelines that used <code>uses:
        tj-actions/changed-files@v44</code> suddenly ran code that walked the
        runner's memory, found every CI secret, and printed them, base64
        encoded, into the public workflow log. Twenty-three thousand
        repositories ran the poisoned commit during the fifteen hours it took
        to notice.
      </p>

      <div class="incident">
        <span class="incident-tag">Anchor &middot; tj-actions/changed-files &middot; CVE-2025-30066</span>
        <p class="incident-headline">
          A retroactive tag rewrite turned a trusted dependency into a secret
          exfiltrator, with no outbound traffic. Just <code>echo</code>.
        </p>
        <p>
          The trick was to make every existing version tag point at the new
          malicious commit, so anyone who had ever depended on the action,
          regardless of which version they thought they pinned, pulled the
          payload. The only repositories that escaped were those that pinned
          to a full commit SHA rather than a tag. The compromised commit had a
          hash. The pinned ones did not match.
        </p>
        <p class="incident-meta">
          <a
            href="https://www.cisa.gov/news-events/alerts/2025/03/18/supply-chain-compromise-third-party-tj-actionschanged-files-cve-2025-30066-and-reviewdogaction"
            >CISA alert</a
          >
          &middot;
          <a
            href="https://www.ox.security/blog/15-hours-of-open-sourced-hell-lessons-learned-from-tj-actions-changed-files/"
            >OX Security timeline</a
          >
        </p>
      </div>

      <p>
        Between source and binary lives a machine. Whatever runs on that
        machine becomes part of every artifact. If the machine is rented, the
        environment is shared, or the build steps are mutable, the attack
        surface grows in ways you cannot see by reading code.
      </p>

      <ul class="defenses">
        <li>
          <span class="defense-name">SHA pinning</span>
          <span class="defense-desc">
            <code>uses: tj-actions/changed-files@a284dc...</code> instead of
            <code>@v44</code>. A commit SHA cannot be silently moved. Tags can.
            This single change made tj-actions a non-event for projects that
            had it.
          </span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="defense-name">SLSA provenance</span>
          <span class="defense-desc">
            A signed attestation, generated by the build platform itself,
            stating "this artifact was built from this commit, by this builder,
            with these inputs." The verifier later checks that the running
            artifact matches a provenance record signed by an identity it
            trusts.
          </span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="defense-name">hermetic / reproducible build</span>
          <span class="defense-desc">
            Build with no network, fully declared inputs, and deterministic
            output. Two independent builders produce byte-identical artifacts
            or one of them is lying. Removes the build machine itself as a
            place to hide a payload.
          </span>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </Stage>

    <Stage
      id="publish"
      num="04"
      title="Publish"
      question="The artifact has a name now. Who put it there?"
    >
      <p class="lead">
        In March 2026, a credential phishing campaign attributed to the
        <em>TeamPCP</em> group reached PyPI and pushed a malicious version of
        <code>litellm</code>, a popular LLM proxy with millions of installs.
        The compromised release was live for forty minutes before PyPI
        quarantined it. Anyone whose CI ran <code>pip install litellm</code>
        in that window pulled a backdoor.
      </p>

      <div class="incident">
        <span class="incident-tag">Anchor &middot; TeamPCP / LiteLLM &middot; 2026-03-24</span>
        <p class="incident-headline">
          A signed identity for who can publish under a name is a different
          question from who wrote the code.
        </p>
        <p class="incident-meta">
          <a
            href="https://securitylabs.datadoghq.com/articles/litellm-compromised-pypi-teampcp-supply-chain-campaign/"
            >Datadog Security Labs analysis</a
          >
          &middot;
          <a
            href="https://docs.litellm.ai/blog/security-update-march-2026"
            >LiteLLM disclosure</a
          >
        </p>
      </div>

      <ul class="defenses">
        <li>
          <span class="defense-name">Sigstore signing</span>
          <span class="defense-desc">
            <code>cosign sign</code> + Fulcio give an artifact a short-lived
            certificate tied to a real workload identity (a GitHub Actions
            workflow, a Buildkite job). No long-lived private keys to steal.
          </span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="defense-name">Rekor transparency log</span>
          <span class="defense-desc">
            Every signature is appended to an immutable, publicly auditable
            log. A signature on its own only proves "someone signed this." A
            log entry proves "and they cannot retroactively unsay it."
          </span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="defense-name">trusted publisher / OIDC</span>
          <span class="defense-desc">
            PyPI and npm now accept short-lived tokens from a specific GitHub
            Actions workflow on a specific repository. A stolen developer
            password no longer publishes a release.
          </span>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </Stage>

    <Stage
      id="distribute"
      num="05"
      title="Distribute"
      question="The name resolves to bytes somewhere. To whose?"
    >
      <p class="lead">
        On 21 April 2026, a worm reached for a different angle: it published
        <code>pgserve</code>, a name that looked enough like a real PostgreSQL
        helper to slip past a tired engineer at <code>npm install</code> time.
        A <code>postinstall</code> hook scanned the developer's machine for
        npm publish tokens, then jumped to PyPI if it found a <code>.pypirc</code>.
      </p>

      <div class="incident">
        <span class="incident-tag">Anchor &middot; pgserve typosquat worm &middot; 2026-04-21</span>
        <p class="incident-headline">
          Distribution is where humans and registries disagree about what a
          name means.
        </p>
        <p class="incident-meta">
          <a
            href="https://www.theregister.com/2026/04/22/another_npm_supply_chain_attack/"
            >The Register coverage</a
          >
          &middot;
          <a
            href="https://thehackernews.com/2026/04/self-propagating-supply-chain-worm.html"
            >The Hacker News writeup</a
          >
        </p>
      </div>

      <ul class="defenses">
        <li>
          <span class="defense-name">namespace scope</span>
          <span class="defense-desc">
            Scoped packages (<code>@org/pgserve</code>) tie a name to an owner.
            Bare names race for whoever publishes first.
          </span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="defense-name">registry attestation</span>
          <span class="defense-desc">
            npm and PyPI now expose, alongside the artifact, the Sigstore
            attestation it shipped with. Clients can verify the chain at
            install time, not "later, when there's an incident."
          </span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="defense-name">install-time policy</span>
          <span class="defense-desc">
            <code>npm install --ignore-scripts</code>, sandboxed
            <code>pip install</code> via PEP 668, container-based dev
            environments. The fewer things a postinstall can read, the smaller
            the worm's launching pad.
          </span>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </Stage>

    <Stage
      id="consume"
      num="06"
      title="Consume"
      question="The artifact is on the box. Should it be allowed to run?"
    >
      <p class="lead">
        A signed, attested, transparently logged artifact is still just bytes
        on disk. The last surface is the moment someone runs them. The defense
        here does not prevent the previous five from being attacked. It refuses
        to play along when they were.
      </p>

      <div class="incident">
        <span class="incident-tag">Anchor &middot; SUNSPOT / SolarWinds &middot; 2020 (historical)</span>
        <p class="incident-headline">
          Once a poisoned binary is on the box, only policy stops it from
          running. SUNSPOT modified Orion at build time, signed it with the
          legitimate signing pipeline, and shipped to thousands of customers
          as an "official" update.
        </p>
      </div>

      <ul class="defenses">
        <li>
          <span class="defense-name">cosign verify</span>
          <span class="defense-desc">
            Refuse to run an image that does not carry a signature from an
            identity you expected: a specific GitHub repository, a specific
            workflow file, a specific builder.
          </span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="defense-name">admission policy</span>
          <span class="defense-desc">
            Kyverno or OPA Gatekeeper turn "trust the registry" into a checked
            assertion. <code>verifyImages</code> at the cluster boundary fails
            closed.
          </span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="defense-name">VEX</span>
          <span class="defense-desc">
            Vulnerability Exploitability eXchange documents say "yes the SBOM
            lists this CVE, no it does not apply because we never call the
            affected function." Lets policy be precise instead of paranoid.
          </span>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </Stage>

    <section class="recap">
      <h2 class="recap-title">Six surfaces, six controls.</h2>
      <p>
        Read top to bottom, no single defense above stops every attack. A
        signed commit does nothing for a tampered tarball. SLSA provenance
        does nothing for a typosquat. Admission policy does nothing for a
        compromised maintainer. The point of the layered model is that the
        attacker has to defeat every one. The defender only has to keep one
        of them honest at any given stage.
      </p>
      <Pipeline />
      <p class="recap-coda">
        Each surface in this page will eventually have its own deeper
        explainer: a runnable demo, a real attestation to inspect, a slider
        between SLSA Build Levels. Phase 2 of <em>chainscope</em>. The map
        comes first.
      </p>
    </section>

    <footer class="article-footer">
      <p class="article-footer-meta">
        <a href="https://github.com/0-draft/chainscope">github.com/0-draft/chainscope</a>
        &middot;
        <a href="https://github.com/0-draft/chainscope/issues"
          >corrections welcome</a
        >
      </p>
    </footer>
  </article>
</Base>

<style>
  .article {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
  }

  .kicker {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.72rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.2em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--color-ink-soft);
    margin: 0;
  }

  .title {
    margin: 0.6rem 0 1.5rem;
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-weight: 500;
    font-size: clamp(2.4rem, 6vw, 3.6rem);
    line-height: 1.05;
    letter-spacing: -0.015em;
    max-width: 22ch;
  }

  .lede {
    font-size: 1.15rem;
    line-height: 1.6;
    margin: 0 0 1rem;
    max-width: 36rem;
    color: var(--color-ink);
  }

  .lede + .lede {
    margin-top: 1rem;
  }

  .article :global(.lede + figure.pipeline),
  .article :global(p.lede + figure.pipeline) {
    margin-top: 3.25rem;
  }

  .article :global(figure.pipeline) {
    margin: 3rem 0 0;
  }

  .article :global(.incident-meta) {
    margin: 0.6rem 0 0;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    color: var(--color-ink-soft);
  }

  .recap {
    margin: 6rem 0 4rem;
    padding-top: 3rem;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--color-rule);
  }

  .recap-title {
    margin: 0 0 1rem;
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-weight: 500;
    font-size: 2.1rem;
    line-height: 1.1;
    letter-spacing: -0.01em;
  }

  .recap p {
    line-height: 1.65;
    max-width: 36rem;
    margin: 0 0 1rem;
  }

  .recap-coda {
    margin-top: 2rem;
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--color-ink-soft);
  }

  .article-footer {
    margin: 5rem 0 0;
    padding-top: 2rem;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--color-rule);
  }

  .article-footer-meta {
    margin: 0;
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    color: var(--color-ink-soft);
  }
</style>
